%N A292529 Decimal expansion of the Pisot constant.
%C A292529 The Pisot constant can be defined as the smallest number gamma such that, for all r < gamma, there exists a monic polynomial P with real coefficients such that |P(e^z)| <= 1 for all complex |z| <= r.
%C A292529 Pisot proves that if an entire function takes integer values at nonnegative integers and is O(e^(r*|z|)) for some r < gamma, then it is a finite sum of terms of the form z^n * alpha^z, where alpha is an algebraic integer and n is a nonnegative integer.
%H A292529 Leonid V. Kovalev, <a href="https://web.archive.org/web/20210117181512/https://calculus7.org/2017/06/17/pisot-constant-beyond-0-843/">Pisot constant beyond 0.843</a> (web.archive.org backup of web page no longer available as of Jan. 2021), June 17, 2017
